The '''ring-billed gull''' ('''''Larus delawarensis''''') is a medium-sized [[gull]] native to North America, breeding in [[Canada]] and the northern [[Contiguous United States]], and wintering mainly in the United States and northern [[Mexico]]. The genus name is from [[Latin]] ''Larus'' which appears to have referred to a gull or other large seabird. The specific ''delawarensis'' refers to the [[Delaware River]].<ref name=job>{{cite book | last= Jobling | first= James A | year= 2010| title= The Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird Names | url= https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling | publisher= Christopher Helm | location = London | isbn = 978-1-4081-2501-4 | pages =[https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling/page/n132 132], 219}}</ref>

==Description==
[[File:17RingBilledGull.jpg|thumb|left|A winter plumage ring-billed gull in flight at Black Butte Lake, California]]
The ring-billed gull is a medium-sized gull, having an average length of {{convert|16.9|to|21.3|in|cm|order=flip}} and a wingspan that ranges from {{convert|41.3|to|46.1|in|cm|order=flip}}. Adults weigh from {{convert|10.6|to|24.7|oz|g|order=flip}}.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Ring-billed Gull Identification, All About Birds, Cornell Lab of Ornithology|url=https://www.allaboutbirds.org/guide/Ring-billed_Gull/id|access-date=2020-09-25|website=www.allaboutbirds.org|language=en}}</ref>

The head, neck and underparts are white; the relatively short bill is yellow with a black ring; the back and wings are silver grey with black wingtips with white 'mirrors'; and the legs are yellow. The eyes are yellow with red rims. This gull takes three years to reach its breeding plumage starting with the largely brown juvenile plumage, its appearance changing with each fall [[moult]].<ref name="Sibley">{{cite book | last=Sibley | first=David Allen | title=The North American bird guide | publisher=Pica Press | publication-place=Mountfield Robertsbridge | date=2000 | isbn=1-873403-98-4 | page=}}</ref><ref name="IUCN" /> 

The average lifespan of an individual that reaches adulthood is 10.9 years.<ref name="IUCN">{{Cite web|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/en|title=The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species|website=IUCN Red List of Threatened Species|access-date=2019-12-21}}</ref> The oldest ring-billed gull on record was observed in [[Cleveland]] in 2021, still alive at the age of 28 years.<ref name="Audubon">{{cite web |last1=Mandelbaum |first1=Ryan F. |title=Oldest Ring-billed Gull on Record Discovered by Cleveland Birder |url=https://www.audubon.org/news/oldest-ring-billed-gull-record-discovered-cleveland-birder |website=National Audubon Society |date=23 March 2021 |access-date=11 April 2021}}</ref>

==Distribution and habitat==
[[File:Ring-billed gull in Red Hook (42799).jpg|thumb|left|Adult in New York]]
{{Listen|filename=Ring-billed Gull colony - Chicago - Andy Mabbett - 01.flac|title=Sounds of a colony|description=Ring-billed gulls vocalizing in a colony}}
The breeding habitat is near lakes, rivers, or the coast across most of Canada, and the northern United States. They [[Bird nest|nest]] [[Bird colony|colonially]] on the ground, often on islands, but also increasingly on flat factory roofs.<ref>{{cite web | title=Distribution and Abundance of Roof-nesting Gulls in the Great Lakes Region of the United States |year=1996 | url=https://kb.osu.edu/server/api/core/bitstreams/86d13c39-884d-5427-84c4-e73f57f42e8e/content | access-date=2024-12-26}}</ref> This bird tends to be faithful to its nesting site, if not its mate, from year to year.

The ring-billed gull is a familiar sight in North American [[parking lot]]s, where it can regularly be found congregating in large numbers.<ref name=birdsnewengland/><ref name=ray/> In some areas, it is displacing less aggressive birds such as the [[common tern]].
[[File:Ring-billed gull in flight (94615) (cropped).jpg|left|thumb|In flight, New York]]
They are [[bird migration|migratory]] and most move south to the Gulf of Mexico and the Atlantic and Pacific coasts of the United States and northern Mexico; some remain in Canada in winter in the mildest areas, on the Pacific coast in southwest [[British Columbia]], and on the Atlantic coast in [[Nova Scotia]].<ref name="Sibley"/>

=== Vagrancy ===
This gull is a regular [[Vagrancy (biology)|wanderer]] to western Europe. In [[Ireland]] and [[Great Britain]] it is no longer classed as a rarity, with multiple birds regularly wintering in those countries, though has become rarer again since about 2010. The peak period of occurrence was in the 1990s with on average 77 each year in Great Britain, but this fell to just 16 per year in the 2010s, and only six per year in 2020–2022 (which, at under ten per year, would reclassify it as an official rarity if continued over a decade).<ref name="BB1">{{cite journal |last1=White |first1=S. |last2=Kehoe |first2=C. |title=Report on scarce migrant birds in Britain in 2022 |journal=British Birds |date=2024 |volume=117 |issue=7 |page=372}}</ref> This contrasts markedly with [[Bonaparte's gull]], another transatlantic visitor, which has increased in Great Britain from averages of six per year to 12 per year over the same period; the reasons for these contrasting changes are unknown.<ref name="BB2">{{cite journal |last1=French |first1=P. |title=Rarities Committee News |journal=British Birds |date=2024 |volume=117 |issue=6 |page=330}}</ref>

==Diet==
[[File:Gull eating a fish.jpg|left|thumb|Eating a fish]]
Ring-billed gulls forage in flight or pick up objects while swimming, walking or wading. They also [[Kleptoparasitism|steal food]] from [[Kleptoparasitism#Birds|other birds]] and frequently [[Scavenger|scavenge]]. They are [[omnivore|omnivorous]]; their diet may include [[insect]]s, [[fish]], [[grain]], [[egg]]s, [[earthworm]]s and [[rodent]]s.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Ring-billed Gull |url=https://www.audubon.org/field-guide/bird/ring-billed-gull |access-date=2024-04-22 |website=Audubon |language=en}}</ref> These birds are opportunistic and have adapted well to taking food when discarded or even left unattended by people. It is regarded as a [[Pest (organism)|pest]] by many beach-goers because of its willingness to steal unguarded food on crowded beaches. The birds congregate at beaches, marinas, docks and parks where people will hand feed them.<ref name="k370">{{cite web |last=MacKenzie |first=Ken | title=The Life and Travels of Ring-billed Gulls |website=Gull Research | url=https://gull-research.org/papers/papers7/gullsmasswildlife.pdf | access-date=2026-01-27}}</ref><ref name=ray>{{cite news |last=Ray |first=C. Claiborne |title=Why do Sea Gulls Like Parking Lots? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/01/science/why-do-sea-gulls-like-parking-lots.html |work=New York Times |date=30 September 2013 |access-date=16 March 2014}}</ref>

The gull's natural predators are [[rat]]s, [[fox]]es, [[dog]]s, [[cat]]s, [[raccoon]]s, [[coyote]]s, [[eagle]]s, [[hawk]]s (although they have been seen in pairs chasing hawks), and [[owl]]s.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Dewey |first=Tanya |last2=Pappas |first2=Janice |title=Larus delawarensis (ring-billed gull) |url=https://animaldiversity.org/accounts/Larus_delawarensis/#predation |access-date=2025-03-09 |website=Animal Diversity Web |language=en}}</ref>

== Status ==
In the late 19th century, the ring-billed gull was hunted for its plumage. Its population has since rebounded, and it is the most common gull in eastern North America, reaching a maximum of around 875,000 breeding pairs in this region (1.75 million adults; excluding non-breeding immatures, and western populations) in around 1990, with a slow decline subsequently, due largely to a deliberate policy to reduce their access to feeding on landfill sites.<ref name="Giroux">{{cite journal | last1=Giroux | first1=Jean-François | last2=Patenaude-Monette | first2=Martin | last3=Lagarde | first3=Florent | last4=Thiériot | first4=Ericka | last5=Brousseau | first5=Pierre | last6=Molina | first6=Pierre | title=The Rise and Fall of Ring-billed Gulls (''Larus delawarensis'') in Eastern North America | journal=Waterbirds | volume=39 | issue=sp1 | date=2016 | issn=1524-4695 | doi=10.1675/063.039.sp101 | pages=87–98 | url=http://www.bioone.org/doi/10.1675/063.039.sp101 | access-date=2026-01-27| url-access=subscription }}</ref> The total population was estimated as 2.55 million birds (including immatures and all populations) in 2006,<ref name = BOW/> and still in 2018.<ref name="iucn status 18 November 2021"/>

